<p>
<seg id=1> The UN Economic Committee of Latin-America and the Caribbean predicted that the regions economic growth would drop to one percent next year. </seg>
<seg id=2> But the committee admitted the situation might be even worse. </seg>
<seg id=3> Now we bring you a report sent by VOA correspondent Mick in South America, read by Tian Ye. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to initial observations by the UN economic committee, this year the economic growth rate in Latin-America and the Caribbean will be 2.3%, a sharp decline from last year's 5.2%. </seg>
<seg id=5> If economic performance in the first half of the year is weak, this year's figures could be even lower. </seg>
<seg id=6> The committee said that despite external shake-ups, the region's economy seems comparatively good. </seg>
<seg id=7> But the worst effects have already appeared, and will continue into next year. </seg>
<seg id=8> The UN economic committee said the tough economic climate in Brazil was reflected in some countries in the south of the continent. </seg>
<seg id=9> These countries are mainly affected by the low price of exported products. </seg>
<seg id=10> The committee said most of the countries chose to increase interest rates to protect their currencies. </seg>
<seg id=11> This hinders economic growth and pushes up the unemployment rate. </seg>
<seg id=12> The report said that if these countries intended to strengthen their competitiveness in the world market by currency devaluation, they would face the risk of inflation ... </seg>
</p>
